1.1:
Heer Is a tretys: A talkyng of þe loue of God. Þis tretys Is a talkyng of þe loue of God; and is mad forto sturen &dot; hem þat hit reden:  to louen him þe more, and to fynde lykyng &dot; and tast in his loue. Hit falleþ for to reden hit &dot; esyliche and softe, so as men may mest &dot; in Inward felyng &dot; and deplich þenkyng &dot; sauour fynden; and þat not beo-dene, but biginnen and leten &dot; in what paas so men seoþ &dot; þat may for þe tyme &dot; &yogh;iuen mest lykynge; and whon men haþ conceyued &dot; þe maters wiþ redyng:  Inward þenkyng &dot; and deoplich sechyng &dot; wiþ-outen eny redyng &dot; vppon þe selue maters, and of such oþere &dot; þat god wol senden &dot; hose wole sechen, schal &yogh;iuen inward si&yogh;t &dot; and felyng in soule &dot; and swetnes wonderful, &yogh;if preyere folwe.  But hose wole in Meditacion &dot; swete fruit fynden:  hit mot be taken in wone &dot; wiþ þreo poyntes þat folewen:  affyaunce, and continuaunce, and louh herte and clene; þat he truste sikerliche &dot; to fynden þat he secheþ, and þat his þou&yogh;t beo harde iset &dot; and ful bisyliche I-kept, and holden him-self vn-worþ &dot; out of godes &yogh;ifte, and wlate on him-seluen &dot; þorw siht of his fulþe.  ¶ Men schal fynden lihtliche þis tretys in Cadence &dot; after þe bigynninge &dot; &yogh;if hit beo riht poynted; & Rymed in sum stude;




to beo more louesum &dot; to hem þat hit reden.  God &yogh;iue vs grace &dot; so for to rede: þat we mowen haue heuene &dot; to vre Mede.  Amen. Ihesu soþ God, Godes sone; Ihesu soþ God soþ mon, mon Maydens child. Ihesu myn holy loue, mi siker swetnesse.  ¶ Ihesu myn herte, my sele, my soule-hele.  Ihesu, swete Ihesu; Ihesu, deore Ihesu; Ihesu, almihti Ihesu.  Ihesu mi lord, my leof, my lyf; myn holy wey, myn hony-ter.  Ihesu, alweldinde Ihesu:  Ihesu þou art al þat I hope.  ¶ Ihesu mi Makere &dot; þat me madest of nou&yogh;t, and al þat is in heuene &dot; and in eorþe.  ¶ Ihesu my Buggere &dot; þ[at] bou&yogh;test me so deore, wiþ þi stronge passion &dot; wiþ þi precious blod, and wiþ þi pyneful deþ on Roode. ¶ Ihesu my Saueour &dot; þat me schalt sauen, þorw þi muchele Merci &dot; & þi muchele mi&yogh;t.  Ihesu my weole & al my wynne:  Ihesu þat al my blisse is inne.  ¶ Ihesu also þat þou art &dot; so feir and so swete, &yogh;it art þou so louelich &dot; louelich and louesum, þat þe holy angeles &dot; þat euere þe biholden:  ben neuere folle &dot; to loken on þi face.  ¶ Ihesu þou art al feir, whon þe sonne a&yogh;eyn þe:  nis bote a schade, and schomeþ a&yogh;eyn þi brihte leor &dot; of hire þesternesse.  ¶ Þou þat &yogh;iuest hire liht &dot; and al þat liht haueþ:  Lihte my þester herte.  Graunte þat þi brihtnesse &dot; clanse my soule:  þat is vnseliche, wiþ sunne foule I-fuiled.  Lord mak hire worþi:  to þi swete wonynge.  Cundele me wiþ þe blisse:  of þi brenninde loue.  ¶ Swete Ihesu my leoue lyf, Let me beo þi seruaunt, and lere me for to loue þe, & mak me for to serue þe &dot; louynde lord:  so þat onliche þi loue &dot; be euer al my lyking, my þou&yogh;t and my longyng; amen, Ihesu heuene kyng. ¶ Swete lord wo is me &dot; þat I am þe so fremde:  Bote also þou hast bodiliche &dot; torned me from þe world, torn me also herteliche &dot; to þe &dot; lord of soþ loue, and studefast beo-leeue; þat I haue no mong, felau&yogh;schupe ne speche, ne non oþer tellyng &dot; wiþ no worldliche þing.  For wel ichot lord, þat fleschlich loue and gostlich, erþliche loue and heuenlich:  mowe none wyse &dot; bedden in a brest. ¶ Hose-euere haue longe defaute of gostly cumfort &dot; and heuenly murþes:  hit is forþi þat he haueþ &dot; or þat he wilneþ to haue:  cumfort of eorþe &dot; þat is fikel and fals, fayleþ whon men lest weneþ &dot; and ate mest neode; hit is I-meynt wiþ bitternesse &dot; and bleendynge of bales.  ¶ Nis no blisse otewiþ &dot; þat hit nis to deore abou&yogh;t, as hony þat me likkeþ &dot; on prikkynde þornes.  ¶ Nis he a sori Chapmon &dot; þat &yogh;iueþ al þat he haþ &dot; for a þing þat nou&yogh;t nis, and leueþ a precious þing Þat beete may alle bales, þat me beodeþ him for nou&yogh;t, & bi-hoteþ him muche meede &dot; þat he hit wole taken?  A derworþe lord &dot; þou beodest vs þi Ioye, þe lykyng of þi deore loue &dot; þe socour of þin helpe; and berest hit on vs stifliche &dot; al wiþ-outen askyng; and þerto þou bi-hotest vs &dot; wiþ þat we wollen hit taken:  heuene-riche blisse &dot; þat is wiþ-outen ende.  And we vs turne þerfro &dot; as þei&yogh; hit nou&yogh;t ne weore; and bugge þe schadewe of þe world, a seynynge of þat is nou&yogh;t, but fikel faylynde and fals &dot; and tollyng to serwe; and &yogh;it ne haue we hit for nou&yogh;t &dot; but buggen hit wiþ bisynesse, wiþ angwysch and daunger &dot; and hard swink and teone.  A Ihesu þin ore, whi haue I likyng In oþer þing þen in þe &dot; þat bou&yogh;test me so deore?  ¶ Whi ne beholde i algates &dot; wiþ e&yogh;e of myn herte, hou þou henge for my loue &dot; streyned on Roode, þin armes wyde I-spradde &dot; þi derlyng to cluppe, wiþ toknyng of trewe loue &dot;




þat sprong out of þi syde?  ¶ Whi nul I beo þi derlyng, and loue þe ouer alle þing, and comen to þi cluppyng, to cleuen in þin armes &dot; and cluppen þe swete?  A derworþe lord &dot; muchel is þi myldeschupe, þat spraddest so þin armes &dot; bodiliche on Roode, and in toknyng of þat &dot; openest þi grace, þat sprad is so wyde &dot; wiþ loueliche tollyng, & open is and redi &dot; to alle þat in synne &dot; beoþ gostliche storuen.  Clepeþ hem to lyue &dot; and to loue-cosses, as Moder doþ hire deore sone &dot; þat hereþ hit wepen:  Takeþ hit in hire armus &dot; and askeþ him so sweteliche:  'Ho leof, ho lef!'  heo doþ him hire bitwenen(!), 'ho wole be bi-clupped &dot; and cusse me swete; who haþ do my deore &dot; who haþ do þe so?'  Heo &yogh;eueþ him hire pappe &dot; and stilleþ his teres.  Þat pappe beo my lykyng, my mournyng my longyng, swete Ihesu heuene kyng:  to souken of my fulle; þat þorw þe speres openyng, in feole mennes gounyng, wiþ dewyng of þi deore blood &dot; stilleþ alle bales.  And wher eny mon wene þat he schal &dot; haue part of þat ilke sok &dot; of þi deore herte &dot; in heuene-riche blisse, and þere be þi derlyng, in þi deore cluppyng, bote he þe heere cluppe &dot; hongynge on Roode, and parte of þi passion &dot; þorw holy meditacion, wiþ loue-lykynde þou&yogh;t &dot; and reuþe of his herte? Nay, sikerliche nay, ne trouwe þat no mon!  ¶ Whose euere wol haue part &dot; þer of þi blisse:  he mot dele wiþ þe &dot; heer of þi pyne.  Nis he nou&yogh;t good felawe &dot; ne felauschupe worþi:  þat nul scoten i þe los &dot; as i þe bi&yogh;ete.  Hym bihoueþ scoten &dot; after his euene:  þat wol be þi felawe &dot; louynde lord; he mot þi steppes folwe &dot; þorw sore and þorw sorwe, in peyne and in pouert &dot; and þolyng of wo, wiþ schome and wiþ schenschupe &dot; &yogh;if hit so falleþ, for to clymbe to þi weole &dot; & lastinde winnes.  Ne trowe no mon wiþ ese &dot; to stei&yogh;e to þe sterres; ne bugge wiþ delyces &dot; þin endeles bl[i]sse.  A swete lord Ihesu, whi wiþ armes of loue &dot; ne cluppe I þe so faste:  þat no þing from þi loue &dot; departe myn herte?  ¶ Whi ne cusse I þe lord &dot; sweteliche in soule:  wiþ a lykinge cos &dot; of a swete menyng &dot; & hertliche þonkyng &dot; of þi gode dedes?  Whi nis me vnworþ &dot; vche worldliche þing, a&yogh;eyn þe muchele delyt &dot; of þi swetnesse?  ¶ Whi ne fele I þe lord &dot; in my brest roote?  ¶ Whi art þou me so fremde &dot; þow þat art so swete?  ¶ Whi ne con I loue þe, and loueneliche wouwe þe, wiþ sweete loue-wordes &dot; and lykynge þou&yogh;tes:  Aller þing swettest &dot; aller þing louelokest; þi worþ and þi worschupe &dot; ne may no tonge telle.  ¶ Weylawey my deore lord, þe vnsely bitternesse &dot; of my foule sunnes!  my worldliche þewes &dot; and flescliche lustes:  aren be-twene þe and me, and lette me to come to þe, and stoppe me þe felyng &dot; of þi swetnesse.  ¶ Mi sunnes haþ me fuiled &dot; wiþ monyfold fulþe, and makeþ me so wlatsum &dot; and fere of þi face, and wrieþ me schomeliche &dot; and worþ i am þi wreche:  þat I ne dar þe nei&yogh;e &dot; loueliche lord, ne comen in þat fulþe &dot; to þin e&yogh;e-sihte, but &yogh;if I fele me lad &dot; wiþ drau&yogh;t of þi grace. ¶ A Ihesu þin ore &dot; what schal þenne þe pris Of þi deore blood don &dot; þat sched was on Roode?  ¶ What schal þe large brok don &dot; of þi softe syde; þe stremes of þe rede blod &dot; þat stryked doun so breme:  of þi derworþe feet &dot; and of þin holy hondes?  Nis hit for to wasschen &dot; sunfole soules?  nis hit forte saluen hem &dot; þat seke ben in sunne?  Ho is þenne vnwasschen &dot; þat haþ þis holy wetyng, þat helinde dewyng &dot; wiþ-Inne his herte?  ¶ Who þar felen him sor &dot; or sek vn-salued, þat salue so mihti &dot; haþ at his wille:  as ofte as he takeþ hit &dot; wiþ




herte in his muynde, wiþ a studefast hope &dot; and trewe be-leeue?  ¶ Euer be þou blessed &dot; myn heueneliche leche, þat madest us of þi-self &dot; so mihti medicyne! As my trust is þer-inne &dot; let hit beo my bote, þat is of alle Medicine &dot; fruit and Roote.  &YOGH;if myn eueles ben muchele &dot; and ouerdon sore, þe mi&yogh;t of þat medicine &dot; is monyfold more.  As wisliche as a drope &dot; of þi derworþe blod &dot; mi&yogh;te wasschen awey &dot; alle Mennes sunnes:  also wisliche lord &dot; þat il[k]e fyf welles, þat of þi blessede bodi &dot; sprongen o blode, my soule mote wasschen &dot; of alle maner sunnes, þat [it] I-fuiled is wiþ &dot; þorw my fyf wittes; of al þat ichaue amis &dot; se&yogh;en wiþ myn e&yogh;en, herd wiþ myn Eren &dot; or tasted wiþ Mouþe, or elles eny wyse a-gult &dot; in sunfol speche, or luþerliche lyked &dot; in sauor of neose, and þat ichaue wiþ eny lyme &dot; misliche feled, and wiþ my flesch sunget &dot; in eny kunnes wyse.  Let þy woundes hele &dot; þe woundes of my soule; þi deþ sle in me &dot; fleschliche lykynge, worldliche leetes &dot; and bodiliche lustes, and make me lyuen in þe &dot; liuinde lord, þat I be to þe world ded &dot; and a-lyue to þe; so þat I mai verreyliche &dot; sigge wiþ þe apostle, Paulus:  Viuo ego, iam non ego, viuit autem in me Christus, «I liue not Ich &dot; but Crist lyueþ in me».  Þat is Poules wordes &dot; and þus for to siggen:  In liue not in lyue &dot; þat I liuede:  but Crist liueþ in me &dot; þorw wonyinde grace, þat from deþ of sunne &dot; me torneþe and quikneþ &dot; to lyf þat is blisful &dot; of gostliche hele, ffrom alle worldliche loue &dot; & fleschliche lustes &dot; al one forto lyuen &dot; in likyng of Crist.  ¶ A deore lord þin ore &dot; wel weore him bigon, þat feled in his soule &dot; þat seli word to siggen; to goderhele weore he boren &dot; & to muche blisse:  for eueri grome were him gome, & eueri wo winne. A Milde Marie &dot; moder of Merci, socour of serweful &dot; and cumfort of care: Nartou lodesterre to alle þo þat in þe séé Of þis worldes anguissche &dot; seilen and faren?  Þou þat art qween of angeles, ladi of alle schaftes; to whom is bitakene &dot; þe cure and þe cumfort &dot; of hem þat hem felen &dot; caytif wrecches, ¶ &yogh;e þat in hor owne e&yogh;en &dot; seon hem-self wrecches, and sechen þin helpe &dot; wiþ trust hope of herte; in þin aduocatye is put &dot; þe cause of vre sunnes, to stonden at domesday &dot; vr aller Iugges mooder, in help & in Meyntenaunce &dot; of vre soule-hele. ¶ Þenk heer on þis wrecche &dot; Moder and Mayden, þat falleþ þe tofote &dot; in hope of þin helpe, cryinde reuþely &dot; after þi grace.  Pese me ladi, for þi muchele merci, to þi derworþe sone &dot; þat Ichaue wiþ sunne &dot; schomeliche and lihtliche &dot; so fele tyme a-gulte.  ¶ Mi sunnes ben so gastliche &dot; grisliche and grete; makeþ me so wlatsum &dot; and stinkinde foule:  þat I ne dar him neih&yogh;en &dot; ne folwe my neode.  I haue wiþ hem willes &dot; my soule forschupped:  from þe liknesse of god &dot; to þe deuel of helle; wraþþed haue I willes &dot; þorw fulþe of my sunne &dot; mi makere mi buggere &dot; þat bou&yogh;te me so deore:  wiþ his derworþe deþ &dot; from þraldam of helle; þat wolde raþer suffre &dot; to dyen on Roode, þen to þolien in his siht &dot; þe wlatynge of sunne.  ¶ Him-self sou&yogh;te my pes &dot; in myn owne gultes, as his hedde be þe gult &dot; moni tyme and ofte:  wiþ sturyng of my concience &dot; & preching of wyse; wiþ hard wrake þat I sau&yogh; &dot; of oþer mennes sunnes; wiþ bi-heste of blisse &dot; & vnimete mede, þat holi writ vs be-hat &dot; &yogh;if we leten sunne; wiþ &yogh;iftus of grace &dot; bodiliche & gostliche, anentes worldliche weole &dot; to don al my wille, and to schilde me from myn enemy &dot; þat I haue ay folewed &dot; and &yogh;iue




me to his wille &dot; and to his luþer lore &dot; and flowen f[ro] þe loue of him &dot; my derworþe lord god:  þat wiþ his derworþe blod &dot; bou&yogh;te me so deore.  He wusch me wiþ cristendam &dot; of Adames sunne, and I me fuylede siþen &dot; mony-fold worse; he helede my soule &dot; þat woundet was þenne Þorw myn eldres gult &dot; ofe Adam & Eue, and I haue slayn hit al out . . . þat I haue feole tyme wrou&yogh;t &dot; and longe ley&yogh;en þer-inne.  ¶ Siþen þorw his grace &dot; he prented in my soule:  þe ymage of him-selue, and I enprented aboue:  þe liknesse of helle.  Allas, my deore ladi, allas what haue I don!  hou haue I chaunged þat prente &dot; and dampned my-seluen!  ¶ Allas þat euere I was so wood &dot; so foule for to fallen! þat me ne schomede not &dot; to worche þat fulþe:  þat is me nou so gryslich &dot; and schomeful to nempne!  Allas whi ne dredde i not &dot; his sute and his werkes, þat is me now so dredful &dot; to nempnen his nome!  He fel willes &dot; þat furst fel foule, but wiþ-outen knowyng &dot; or warnyng of wreche; ac I was war þerbi &dot; and bi mony oþure, bi warnyng and wissyng &dot; on mony-maner halue, and fel in þe selue &dot; and in moni mo.  Hee fel in pruide &dot; þat hedde sum matere, siþen þat he was so feir &dot; and so briht an angel; and I fel in þe selue &dot; wiþ-outen eny matere, þat nou&yogh;t haue of my-self &dot; but sunne and flesches fulþe.  He fel ones &dot; and I fel feole siþes.  He a&yogh;eyn his makere &dot; and I a&yogh;eyn my makere &dot; and myn eft makere &dot; a&yogh;eynes my lord:  þat bou&yogh;te me wiþ his herte blod &dot; and &yogh;af me al him-seluen.  He forsok vr lord god &dot; þat suffrede him to gulten, and wiþ-outen sparyng &dot; drof him al to wreche; and I forsok þat ilke lord &dot; þat letteþ my gultus, and secheþ me and folweþ me, whon so euere I from him fle, and calleþ me loueliche &dot; to &yogh;ift of his grace.  ¶ Allas allas nou fynde I me grisloker in my gultes, þen þe grislihed of him &dot; þat helle gryseþ offe.  ¶ Allas &yogh;if I seo my-self &dot; I ne may soffre my-self; and &yogh;if i ne seo my-self nou&yogh;t &dot; þenne gyle I my-self . . . . þen stynkinde careyne, and muche more wlatsum &dot; bifore godes face: þen eny fulþe so foul &dot; þat eny mon may þenken; so þat me gryseþ of my-self &dot; and wlate of my fulþe; þat I ne may soffre mi-self &dot; þat wrou&yogh;te haue al þis serwe.  A lord þyn ore, þat I may sike sore!  Whi ne griseþ of me &dot; boþe my mete and my drynk, my schroud and al oþer þing &dot; þat me scholde helpe? Hou may rihtwysnesse þole . . . . þat þer ne riseþ a&yogh;eyn me &dot; alle þyne schaftes, wiþ schome & wiþ schendschupe &dot; wiþ gounyng & wiþ spornyng, to fihten on þis traytur &dot; þis tiraunt and þis tormentor, þat haþ al his schappere &dot; so fouliche dispiset?  ¶ Whi nam I hunted wiþ hem &dot; foule as a dogge?  For þei mowe alle crie &dot; and siggen in heore kuynde:  «Þees is þe foule corselyng &dot; þat haþ vr aller makere &dot; þat maade vs to his worschupe &dot; so schomeliche offendet; þat vseþ vs in his werkes &dot; to schome of vr lord.  ¶ Þees is he þat more bey&yogh; &dot; in wille & in werk, to þe deueles tollyng &dot; þen to godes drawyng, and more haþ rewarde &dot; to þe deueles gyle, þen to godes benfe&yogh; &dot; þat bou&yogh;t him on Rode; and hedde more likyng &dot; in þe Malice of þe deuel, þen he hedde delyt &dot; in Godes goodnesse; and ches muchel raþere &dot; to beo þe deueles cundle, þen wiþ endeles lyf &dot; godes child of heuene.  ¶ Whon god daunselede him muchel &dot; & worschuped him feyre:  he ne set hit at nou&yogh;t &dot; ne dredde not his wreche; but more dredde to wraþþen &dot; a worldliche wrecche:  þen schomeliche offenden &dot; god þat him wrou&yogh;te; and more was aschomet &dot; to don in monnes siht an eþeliche




truifle &dot; of vnsittyng þing:  þen mony a foul sunne &dot; in siht of god almi&yogh;ti. ¶ More him delyted &dot; forte enbrace Mock, and styngk of worldliche Mok &dot; þat gyleþ so foule, þen baþen in þe lykyng &dot; & in þe loue-cluppyng, in þe brennynge loue &dot; of þe holygost.  ¶ Al-beo þat on defendet &dot; and a&yogh;eyn þe lawe, and þat oþur nomeliche &dot; I-&yogh;iuen vs in heste.  Þat on is wonnen wiþ swynk &dot; & wiþ muchel anguissche, and endeþ atte laste &dot; wiþ &yogh;eldyng of wreche; Trauayle þe wynnyng, drede in þe keping, serwe in þe leosyng &dot; and helle at þe ende.  ¶ Þat oþur nis not so deore a-bouht &dot; bute is ful muche menskeful, wiþ waxinde likyng &dot; & bodiliche fyndyng, & bringeþ atte laste &dot; endeles blisse. God seiþ hit him-self &dot; þat hose secheþ him furst, & ouer al oþur þing &dot; askeþ his blisse, al þat him be-houeþ &dot; to bodiliche neode, schal be graunted þe[r]-wiþ &dot; and &yogh;iuen in þat boone — Luc.: Querite primum regnum dei &c. // Þis is he þat al day &dot; torneþ god his hindewine, and hertliche louteþ &dot; to cluppe worldes dweole.  ¶ Þis is þat blynde wrecche &dot; þat in his owne e&yogh;en Weneþ him so vertuous &dot; & is ful of vices; leeteþ him feir and freoly &dot; and haþ þe deueles liknesse; and weneþ þat he beo witti &dot; and al ful of slei&yogh;þe:  and lokeþ on his chaffare &dot; þat he is afolte, þat sold haþ his soule &dot; for stinkynde lustes, and chaungeþ god for þe deuel &dot; and heuene for helle.  He halt him ful dou&yogh;ti, stalworþe & hardi, and al day is ouercomen &dot; of him þat haþ no mi&yogh;te Forte wiþ-stonde þe moste wrecche of þe world:  þat wolde a&yogh;eyn him fihte.  He leteþ him gentil &dot; and is þe deueles þral, and demeþ hem wrecches &dot; and makeþ hem his harlotes, þat ben so gentil of blod &dot; þat god is heore fader.  Þus he lokeþ him-self &dot; wiþ a fals e&yogh;e, seoþ þat þat is nou&yogh;t &dot; and demeþ al wrong.  Hit is þe deueles Mirour &dot; þat he in lokeþ, and þe fendes argumens &dot; þat him þinkeþ resouns, þat he bobbeþ him wiþ &dot; and ledeþ as him lykeþ.»  A Ihesu Crist þin ore, hou schal I euer dry&yogh;en &dot; to þenken on þi domes:  a&yogh;eynes my gultes &dot; þat alle þyne schaftes &dot; þus harde mouwen acusen?  And not onliche þus, but &yogh;it mowe þei cri&yogh;en &dot; and siggen in heore wyse:  ¶ «Þees is þe deueles Maumet, þat haþ vs alle wrongliche Vsed in his werkes &dot; a&yogh;eynes vr kuynde.  He hedde godes liknesse &dot; and torned him-self out of þat In to þe liknesse &dot; of vch of vs alle; he is more eorþly &dot; þen euer was eorþe, fikelore þen þe wynt, more veyn þen is þe eir, hattore in his lustes &dot; þen is þe fuir þat brenneþ; hardore þen eny ston &dot; of wikkede herte:  a&yogh;ein his euencristne &dot; þat Crist representen; caldore of charite &dot; þen forst in his kuynde.  ¶ What schal I more siggen?  he ne dredde not god &dot; ne mon he ne louede, but mengede his owne wikkednesse &dot; among moni oþure, and dude þat in him was &dot; ladde hem his weies, and was to hem ensaumple &dot; and ledere to synne, wiþ vnclene speches &dot; wiþ lecherous lokynges, wiþ schrewede dedes &dot; and mony luþer leetes.  ¶ Ne þhou&yogh;te him nou&yogh;t inouh &dot; þat godes deþ on Roode Weore lost anontes him-self &dot; but anontes mony mo, and dude þat in him was &dot; as þe deueles promotour &dot; and godes oune traytor, to leden hem to sunne.  He bar him as he weore a god &dot; siþen þat he nolde Beo ilad bi godes wille &dot; ne bi no lawe, but as him lyked him-self &dot; a&yogh;eyn godes hestes Strayen out of lawe &dot; in wrong and in outrage, as mon al laweles:  & don what him luste.  ¶ &YOGH;if God ne dude for him &dot; al þat he wolde:  he gruyned a&yogh;eynes him &dot; as þau&yogh; he weore his knawe; and &yogh;if he eny tyme &dot; letted for [t]o




sunne, hit was not for godes loue &dot; but for Monnes drede, or for bodiliche harm: or worldliche enchesun.  Boþe of goode and of euel:  he wolde be loued, as þei&yogh; he weore god self &dot; of whom alle þing þat is, boþe goode an vuel, is ordeynt for goode.  ¶ What schal I of him &dot; more speke?  his pruide passeþ Lucifer &dot; þat fel into helle; his gult Adames gult &dot; þat cast him out of paradis, and nou&yogh;t onliche him &dot; but alle monkuynde.  For þey hedde muchel þat hem drowe &dot; to be proud offe, and he nedde but wrecchednesse:  þat scholde him wiþdrawe.» Allas my foule fulþe:  and my muchel vnsleihþe!  What schal I nou to rede? whoder schal I now gon?  Wher schal I me beo-turnen &dot; nou alle þing is þus risen &dot; a&yogh;eynes me one:  and wondreþ þus on me?  ¶ A&yogh;eynes alle schaftes:  haue I mis-taken, and my deore lord god:  luþurliche dispiset, and alle his holy angeles:  greuousliche I-erred, and alle his holy halewen:  foule deshonoured, and myn euencristne:  in mony maner greued, and alle creatures:  haue I mis-vset, Anselmus.  A serwe and sikyng, cri&yogh;ing & gronyng, wher be &yogh;e ryue:  &yogh;if &yogh;e here faylen?  ¶ wher be &yogh;e feruent:  &yogh;if &yogh;e heere slaken?  Nou ne wot I whoderward &dot; I may me best bi-tornen, ffor I haue maked me fon:  in alle kunnes halue.  ¶ Allas allas my lord god &dot; stured is to wraþþe, and no þing ne haue I me laft &dot; þat al nis offendet:  þat scholde me helpe &dot; or eny good wille.  ¶ &YOGH;if I ha wraþþed þe sone, nis þe moder erred?  And &yogh;if þe Mooder be wroþ, hou is þe sone quemed?  Who schal pese me wiþ þe sone &dot; &yogh;if þe Moder beo my fo?  ¶ Or who schal me geten þe Moder loue &dot; &yogh;if þe sone me hate?  ¶ But deore lord of Merci &dot; þat art al merci, and þou his deore Mooder &dot; þat art ful of grace: &yogh;if I haue ow boþe a-gult &dot; ne be &yogh;e ful of Merci?  And wherto schulde merci &dot; &yogh;if gultus ne weore?  ¶ Schal þe Malice of myn euel &dot; passen oure goodnesse? or alle myne sunnes:  ben more þen oure Milce?  ¶ Ne art þou lord bi-come mon &dot; and taken hast vr kuynde?  And þou my deore ladi, bicomen art his Mooder?  ¶ and hast al þi menske &dot; in heuene & in eorþe, for resun of sunful &dot; and wreche to slaken?  ¶ Þou lord bicome mon &dot; and a Mylde Maidenes barn, þat hard deþ and schendful:  þoledest for þyn enemys; and þou his deore Mooder &dot; wiþ Maydenes menske, þe swerd of þi peyne:  þurlede þi soule — animam tuam pertransiuit gladius. And þat wolde &yogh;e þole &dot; for Merci al-one:  to sechen hem þat weoren at-rei&yogh;t &dot; and drawen hem þat fledden.  ¶ And I þat seche Merci &dot; and truste in &yogh;or Merci, and knoweleche my gult &dot; wiþ sore herte-sykes, schulde fayle Merci &dot; þer welle is of Merci, þat is to alle synful &dot; so ryf and so large? ¶ Wher is þenne þat word &dot; of cumfort & blisse, þat þou seidest þi-self &dot; derworþe lord: Nolo mortem peccatoris, «I nul not, þou seist, þe deþ of þe synful, but I wole he turne &dot; and stunte of his sunne, and ryse to my grace &dot; in lyf wiþ-outen ende».  And þat also þou seist: In quacumque hora ingemuerit, saluus erit, «Whon so euere þe sunful &dot; forþinkeþ his sunne, & wilneþ for to stunten, anon he schal be saued»?  ¶ Ne seidest þou not lord &dot; to þe þeef on Roode, þat euer seþþen he couþe &dot; hedde I-vsed þefþe, þat in þe selue day &dot; he scholde ben in blisse?  and for no more decert &dot; but for he kneu&yogh; his gultes, and þe for his saueour &dot; & asked þi Merci?  Ne was he put in no delay &dot; to ligge longe in peyne, but seidest so redily &dot; wiþ so mylde steuene: Hodie mecum eris in paradyso. Nart þou derworþe lord &dot; þe Merciable ffader, þat þou liknest þe to &dot; as




telleþ þe gospel, ¶ þat whon so euere þe luþer sone &dot; beo he neuer so gulti, þenkeþ in his herte &dot; to seche þi Merci:  anon þou seost him a-fer &dot; in þat ilke þou&yogh;t, and eornest a&yogh;eynest him &dot; wonderliche swiþe, and er he speke eny word &dot; but in þe þou&yogh;t al-one, so þat hit be studefast &dot; and wil for to rysen, ¶ þou fallest aboute his nekke &dot; and cluppest him & cussest, wiþ chere ful blisful &dot; & welcomest him hom, and clepest alle frendes &dot; and makest a feste, slest þe fatte feste-calf &dot; for þi sone sake, and biddest hem beo glade &dot; and bliþe blissen wiþ þe, þat þi sone is founden &dot; þat þou heddest loren — Occurrit filio prodigo videns eum a longe. And whon þow heng on Rode &dot; preyedest to þi ffader &dot; for þat ilke traytors &dot; þat duden þe to þe deþ: Pater ignosce illis, quia nesciunt quid faciunt. And hedden alle Merci &dot; þat hit wolden asken; and of alle þing &dot; most was þi &yogh;ernyng, þat þei wolden eny wey &dot; þi merci vnderfonge.  Þat Merci is so plentiuous &dot; so redi and so large:  profred and presed &dot; euer ar men hit asken.  For asken hit ne mai me not &dot; ne haue þat ilke grace, but þou hit specialich &dot; put hit in vr wille.  And &yogh;it of alle þinge &dot; þen furstest þou most &dot; aftur heor soulus &dot; þat merci for-soken.  Ne art þou lord vr fader, and maked vs hast þin eires &dot; of þi grete blisse, and in þe pater noster &dot; biddest clepe þe so, and þat we asken of þe &dot; al þat vs likeþ, and þat not luitel &dot; but al hol þi-seluen, wiþ al þat vs nedeþ &dot; to bodi and to soule?  ¶ Hou schulde euere þe child &dot; failen of his askyng:  anentes such a ffader &dot; þat muchel more loueþ þe child, þen he doþ his owne bodi &dot; or deeþ þe child him-seluen?  Nai sikerliche nay &dot; ne may he neuer faylen Of þat or better þerfore, but &yogh;if hit beo mis-asked.  ¶ And al-beo þou vr ffader &dot; Lord in persone, of þe ffader þou art bicome vr broþer &dot; in persone of Crist; vr Iuge & vr domes-mon &dot; þat al þe world schal demen, art bi-comen vr broþer &dot; of flesch and of blod.  ¶ And sei[st] derworþe lord &dot; þorw þe prophete, as fader al ful of loue &dot; wordes so swete: Numquid potest mater obliuisci filii vteri sui:  & si illa obliuiscatur, ego non obliuiscar tui, ¶ «Þou&yogh; þe moder mi&yogh;te for-&yogh;eten &dot; þe child þat heo bar, þou ne mai&yogh;t for&yogh;ite mon &dot; þat wole to þe callen»; but seist þat al þi likynge &dot; & al þi delices, euer is wiþ vs for to wone &dot; and dwelle wiþ mon — Salomon: Delicie mee, esse cum filiis hominum. A þou Blisful moder &dot; þat art vr oune Moder, þou ne askest neuer wreche &dot; of no monnus sunnes, but were þe gult neuer so gret &dot; ne sunnes so monye, askest ay merci &dot; wiþ moderliche reuþe; and þerfore bicome þou &dot; Ihesu Cristes moder, & moder of sunfole &dot; to bringen hem to grace.  ¶ How scholde I desafyen &dot; to fallen in &yogh;or grace:  þat am &yogh;ou boþe so sibbe &dot; &yogh;oure sone and &yogh;or broþur, and þou lord my Iuge &dot; and myn oune broþer, ¶ and þou ladi my Moder &dot; and my Iugges Modur, and of þe selue Iuge &dot; asignet to my counseil, to be myn aduocatrix &dot; beo-fore him in þe dom!  ¶ Wher may be grace &dot; &yogh;if heer beo reddour; or eny hope founden &dot; &yogh;if hit heere fayle?  hou scholde I euer dreden &dot; to fynden alle fauour, and vnimete merci &dot; bi-fore so sib a Iuge, ¶ þat haueþ me so frendly &dot; &yogh;if þat I seche merci &dot; while tyme is of merci &dot; bi-tau&yogh;t so leof an helpe?  ¶ Who schal my cause sauen &dot; &yogh;if heo ne may suffisen, þat haþ hit vndertaken &dot; þat and alle suche, and haþ hit of offyse &dot; for sunfol to causen: and is þe Iuge hire owne &dot; to forþeren al hir wille? ÞEnk on þi Caytyf &dot; lord God almihti, and þou his Mylde Mooder &dot; þat ben so ful of Merci; þow Lord ffauerynde &dot; and þou ladi be-sechinde; let me neuer faylen &dot; þat I Merci ne fynde; or elles sei me where &dot; is eny of more Merci, and more mihtful þen &yogh;e &dot; and largore of grace, ¶ þat in &yogh;our defaute &dot; whon &yogh;e me forsaken, schul my neode beeten &dot; and graunten my bone.  ¶ But siþen onliche in ow &dot; & in non noþur, is welle of alle Merci &dot; þat euermore floweþ:  ffor þat muchel Merci &dot; clanse my soule, and wasch hit of þat fulþe &dot; þat hit is fuyled wiþ:  ¶ þat I þorw or grace &dot; askape þat wreche, þat is me worþiliche &dot; for gult of my dedes; and schild me from þat serwes &dot; nou and euer-more, þat beþ to þe dampnede &dot; greyþed in helle; þat I wiþ alle þo þat ben &dot; blisful in heuene, may ow boþe blessen &dot; ay wiþ-outen ende, amen. Ihesu my derworþe lord &dot; Ihesu myn oune Fader; swete Ihesu heuene kyng, mi druri my derlyng, mi deoring mi louyng, myn hony-brid my swetyng; myn hele & myn hony-ter, min hony-lyf min halewy.  Swettore art þou þen hony &dot; or Milk in Mouþe, Meode Meþ or pi&yogh;ement &dot; maad wiþ spices swete, or eny lykinde licour &dot; þat ou&yogh;wher may be founden.  Ho ne may loue lord &dot; þi leoue lofsum leore?  What herte is so ouer-hard &dot; þat ne may to-melte, in þe monyg of þe &dot; loueliche lord?  And ho ne may loue þe &dot; swete Ihesu?  For in-wiþ þeselue aren &dot; alle þinges gedered, þat euer may maken eny mon &dot; loueworþ to oþer.  ¶ Feirnesse, louesum leor, flesch whit vnder schroud, makeþ mony mon beo bi-loued &dot; and þe more deore.  ¶ Summe freodam & largesse &dot; þat leuere is: menskeliche to &yogh;iuen &dot; þen quedliche to wiþ-holden.  ¶ Summe wit and wisdam &dot; and hap of þe world.  ¶ Summe Miht and strengþe &dot; to ben kud Kene in fiht &dot; his riht to defenden.  ¶ Summe nobleye & hendelek &dot; and gentrise of kuynde.  ¶ Summe gret Cortesye &dot; and loþles leetes.  ¶ Summe mylde and Mekenesse &dot; & deboner herte, wiþ swete louereden &dot; and godliche dedes.  ¶ And &yogh;it ouer alle þeose &dot; kuynde mest; sibbe frendes &dot; vchon louen oþur.  Now my derworþe loue &dot; my swete lyf my lykyng, my louelichest leof &dot; myn herte and myn halewy, mi longyng mi mournyng &dot; mi soule swetnesse:  þou art lufsum of leor &dot; mi swete Ihesu; þow art also schene &dot; þat alle angeles lyf:  is to biholden &dot; þi loueliche face.  ¶ For þi leor is so briht &dot; and vnimete lofsum, þat &yogh;if þe for-wariede &dot; þat wallen in helle, mihten hit [se] wiþ e&yogh;en &dot; and loken þer-onne, al þat pyninde pich &dot; þat þei wallen Inne, ne wolde hem þinke &dot; bote a softe baþ baþinge; ¶ ffor &yogh;if hit so mihte beo &dot; derworþe lord, leuere hem were euer-more &dot; in wo forte dwelle, and on þi lofsum leor &dot; euer-more to loke, þen in alle blisse ben &dot; euer wiþ-outen ende, and of þat bri&yogh;t blisful leor &dot; forgon þat swete sihte. ¶ Þou art so schene & so briht &dot; þat þe sonne weore desk, &yogh;if hit to þi blisful leor &dot; mihte ben I-euenet.  ¶ &YOGH;if I wol loue eny mon &dot; for his feirnesse, forsoþe derworþe lord &dot; I wol loue þe, mi leoue blessede lord:  moder-sone feyrest, of alle þing swettest &dot; founden in tast.  ¶ A swete Ihesu gode leof &dot; let me beo þi seruaunt, and lere me for to loue þe &dot; louynde lord, þat onliche þe loue of þe &dot; be euer al my likyng, mi &yogh;eornyng mi longyng, mi þou&yogh;t and al mi worching.  Amen. BOte my swete lord &dot; for þat sibbe frendes Kuyndeliche loueþ hem &dot; vchon to oþer, þou cloþedest þe wiþ oure flesch &dot; mon boren of wommon; þou toke




of hire swete flesch &dot; wiþ-outen hire wemmyng &dot; monkuynde follich, to þole al þat mon mai þole, and don al þat mon doþ &dot; wiþ-oute synne one, and bicom vr broþur &dot; of Fader and of Mooder, to maken hol [loue] vnbeden &dot; bituenen vs alle. ¶ Who is þenne þat ne may &dot; & ou&yogh;te to be kuynde, to louen his oune broþur of flesch and of blod?  ¶ Nou my swete Ihesu &dot; my derworþe broþur:  my sibbe kun haue I leeued &dot; for þe loue of þe, and þei&yogh; heo me forsaken &dot; ne reccheþ me noþing, whiles þat I mai haue þe &dot; al one for hem alle.  ¶ For &yogh;if I þe haue &dot; what scholde I more asken?  I nouh þat me neod is &dot; ne may me frendes lakken.  Þou art me more þen Fader &dot; more þen Moder; Broþur or Suster &dot; or eny worldliche frend, nou&yogh;t aren hem to telle &dot; a&yogh;ein þe al one.  A swete Ihesu &dot; mi derworþe broþer, of flesch and of blod &dot; of fader & of moder:  ¶ Mi swete derworþe lord &dot; let me beo þi seruaunt, & teche me forte loue þe &dot; benyngne lord, þat onliche þe loue of þe &dot; beo al my likyng.  ¶ Wel artou swete &dot; and louelich ouur alle, ffor in þe one is founden &dot; þe pris of alle beute, þe pris of al richesse &dot; of loue and of largesse, of wit & of wisdam &dot; of miht and of strengþe. In þe is pris of sibreden &dot; & of alle frendschupe, of al loueliche þing &dot; þat mon may wiþ [in] loue ben.  But ouer al oþur þing &dot; þat makeþ þe so louelich, & so loueworþ to me &dot; my derworþe lord, vnimete more:  þin ouerharde hurtes, þi schome and þi woundes &dot; þi pyne & þi passiouns, þi deore deþ on Roode &dot; þat was so schendful for me; heo asken al hol my loue &dot; and reuen al myn herte. A swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; let me beo þi seruaunt, and lere me forte loue þe &dot; louynde lord, þat onliche þe loue of þe &dot; beo euer al my likyng, mi &yogh;eornyng and my longyng, my þou&yogh;t & al mi worching.  amen. BOte moni for richesse &dot; lemmon cheoseþ; ffor eueriwher mai men &dot; wiþ catel loue chepen.  ¶ Bot is þer eny Ricchore þen þou &dot; my leue lyf my lemmon, þat richeliche regnest &dot; in heuene & in eorþe?  Þou art kud Cayser &dot; þat al þis world weldeþ; ffor as þe prophete seiþ &dot; Dauid in his psalme: Domini est terra & plenitudo eius, «þin is þe eorþe &dot; and al þat þer-in woneþ».  þin is þe heuene &dot; and al þat þerin lyueþ; þin is al þe wyde world &dot; and al þat þer is inne.  ¶ Al is þin my swetyng &dot; and al þow wolt hit &yogh;eue me, &yogh;if I wiþ al myn herte &dot; al-one wol þe.  But þou lord þi-seluen &dot; art wiþ-outen ende, vnymete more worþ &dot; þen ben alle þeose.  Þerfore wol I loue þe &dot; my leue lyf my deore, and al-one for þi loue &dot; alle þinges leten, þat mihte myn herte &dot; from þi loue leden, or ben encheson þerof &dot; to louen þe þe lasse.  [A swete Ihesu &c.] BOte what is Richesse worþ &dot; or muche forto welden, þer wiþ-outen largesse &dot; freodam lakkeþ?  ¶ And ho is freore þen þou &dot; or largore of &yogh;ifte, þat furst madest al þis world &dot; and &yogh;eue hit to my wille.  Þow &yogh;eue me such lordschupe &dot; ouer alle þi schaftes, and puttest vnder my feet &dot; al þat þou schope.  But I hit wikkedliche fordude &dot; þoru my foule synnes.  And þou for þi freodam &dot; &yogh;af for me þi-selue, to leese me from þraldam &dot; þat I was put inne.  ¶ &YOGH;if I eny þenne wole &dot; for largesse louen, þe al one wol I louen &dot; swete Ihesu.  For oþure þat ben large men &dot; and corteis I-kudde, &yogh;iuen of heore goodes &dot; after þat hem lykeþ:  but þou sweete Ihesu &dot; largest of alle, ne &yogh;euest not one of þi good &dot; to wouwe wiþ þi lemmon, bote [&yogh;eue] þi-self for me &dot; in prys of my soule, þat




þin owne herte-blood &dot; ne woldest not wiþholden.  So derworþe dreweri &dot; ne so deore &yogh;ifte, ne &yogh;af neuer in þis world &dot; lemmon to oþur.  And also þat þou for me &dot; &yogh;af so þy-seluen, þou hast me hi&yogh;ed to þe &dot; and &yogh;af me al þi-seluen, to sitten on þi riht hond &dot; coround in þi riche, wiþ euer-lykynde loue &dot; to regnen in blisse.  ¶ Who is þenne largore &dot; þen þou art of &yogh;ifte, or so loue-worþi &dot; [as þou] swete Ihesu?  Wher may me eny loue &dot; so worþiliche setten, whose secheþ eny þing &dot; þat eny loue askeþ, as on þe my lemmon &dot; þat art loue-welle, and &yogh;eldest alle þat þe louen &dot; wellynde stremes?  A swete Ihesu &c. But largesse is luyte worþ &dot; and luyte loue worþi, þat riht rulynde wit &dot; and wisdam wonteþ.  &YOGH;if I wol eny þenne loue &dot; for wit or for wisdam, þen wol i loue [þe] &dot; swete Ihesu; for þi wit is wonderful &dot; and wiþ-outen make.  ¶ Þou art wisdam i-clept &dot; and wit of þi fader; ffor he þorw þat wisdam made &dot; boþe heuene and eorþe, and als his swete willes was &dot; al þis world wrou&yogh;te, schop þe sonne and þe séé &dot; and alle maner schaftes, and al he dihte wonderliche &dot; as hit best semede.  In-wiþ þe my leue lyf &dot; is welle of alle wisdam, þat haþ so wonderliche wit &dot; sprad so wyde-where:  al þat is and euer was &dot; and euer schal betyden, al hit is before-hond &dot; to þi wit knowen.  Ne may þer-wiþ no wisdam &dot; in al þis world be founden, bute hit of þat welle &dot; of þi wit streme.  ¶ A swete Ihesu swete lef &dot; swettest ouer alle, &yogh;if me wit to loue þe, let me beo þi seruaunt, þat I euere serue þe, and teche me forte qweme þe &dot; louynde lord, so þat onlich þi loue be euer al my likyng. BOte mony mon for strengþe &dot; and mony for his hardischupe, is ofte muchel i-leten of &dot; and loued and honoured.  And is eny so hardi, so bold and so dou&yogh;ti:  as þou art my leue lyf &dot; founden in a-say?  Nay forsoþe swete lef &dot; þou berest þe pris of alle; for þow þi-self al one &dot; ne dreddest not þyn oune bodi, to fihten a-&yogh;eyn alle &dot; þe deuelen of helle; þe w&yogh;uche of hem alle &dot; so is lest lodlich, mi&yogh;te he him schewen &dot; [in] þe makyng þat he is, alle scholde ben agast &dot; and grysen of him one, ffor no mon mihte him i-seo &dot; and in his wit wone, but &yogh;if þi grace special &dot; baldes his herte.  Þou art &yogh;it þer-wiþ &dot; so vnymete mihti, þat wiþ [þi] deore hondes &dot; nayled on Roode, þou bounde helle-dogges &dot; and raftes hem heore preye, þat þei faste helden &dot; for Adames sunne; and as a kene kempe &dot; robbedest helle, and laddest out þi deore leef &dot; þat is monnes soule, to þi bri&yogh;te boure &dot; ful of alle blisse, to wonen in þi cluppyng &dot; euer wiþ-outen ende.  ¶ And þerfore &yogh;if me lykeþ &dot; stalworþe lemmon, louen þenne wol I þe &dot; louely Ihesu, þat art al mihti &dot; and strengest of alle.  Strengþe me to loue þe &dot; [swete Ihesu], þat al my feblesse mai&yogh;t &dot; strengþen at þi wille, and wiþ þin hei&yogh;e hardinesse &dot; bi ni&yogh;tes and bi dayes, a&yogh;eyn my wiþerwines &dot; bolden mi soule.  A swete Ihesu mi&yogh;ti leof &dot; strengest of alle, strengþe me to loue þe, let me beo þi seruaunt &dot; derworþe lord, &c. Noble men and gentil &dot; and of hei&yogh; kuynde:  mony wimmen leeten &dot; menske forte loue.  A swete Ihesu Merci &dot; on what herre mon, mai I sette my loue &dot; &yogh;if þat I þe lete?  Wher is eny gentilore &dot; þen þi-self founden?  Þou art þat ilke kynges sone &dot; þat þis world weldeþ, and kyng wiþ þi ffader &dot; kyng of alle




kynges, and lord al-mi&yogh;ti &dot; lord of alle lordes.  And &yogh;it art þow ouer þis &dot; boren of mylde Marie, of Dauides kunreden &dot; þe kyng of Abrahames blod.  Of herre cunreden þen þou art &dot; nis non vnder sonne.  Louen wol I þenne þe &dot; swete Ihesu, as þe gentileste leof &dot; þat euer was in eorþe, þat neuer was no lac &dot; ne last wiþ I-founden; and þat com þe nomeliche &dot; of kuynde of þi fader, of whom is al gentilrie &dot; and cortesye sprongen.  Let me be þi seruaunt &dot; gentil and hende, and lere me forte loue þe &dot; my derworþe lord, so þat in þe loue of þe &dot; my lyking and my Ioye, wiþouten eny oþur mong &dot; euer be rooted fast. MEkenesse and myldeschupe &dot; are swete loue-tacches, and makeþ ofte mony mon &dot; leof and dere.  And þou Ihesu my leoue leof &dot; for þi muchele Mekenesse, as witnesseþ holi writ &dot; to lomb were þou euenet.  For a&yogh;eyn alle schomes & serwes &dot; þat men duden þe, neuer ne opnedest þou þi mouþ &dot; to grucchen a&yogh;eyn. And &yogh;it to eken al þat &dot; al þe schome & sunne, þat synful wrecches of þis world &dot; vche day recheles &dot; don a&yogh;eyn þi godhed &dot; as þou no god ne were, þou þolest al myldelich, and takest hit lihtlich, ne takest not sodeynlich &dot; wreche of vr gultes; but þorw þi muchele myldeschupe &dot; abydest vs longe, euer sechinde loue &dot; & beodyng of grace.  And þerfore my lemmon &dot; my Ioye & my blisse, euer glad mai I ben &dot; & blisful to wisse, þe false murþes of þis world &dot; to leuen & misse, & euer resten in þe &dot; to cluppen & cusse.  A swete Ihesu my leoue leof &dot; my loueliche lemmon, mi derworþe derlyng &dot; mi soule swetnesse:  ¶ þreo foos fihten &dot; a&yogh;eynes me faste:  þe false world and my flesch &dot; þe þridde is þe deuel; ¶ þe world to make me fals &dot; and tolle me to þefþe; ¶ mi flesch to mony fulþes &dot; of vntounes lustes; ¶ þe deuel wiþ wiþ his sleihþes &dot; and wiþ his queynte crokes, to trappe me loþliche &dot; to drawe me to helle.  And for I was so ouer-arwh &dot; and wok of my-selue, þei be-segede me &dot; and kene besetten:  And maden me mony a res &dot; wiþ grennynde beere, fful grimme and ful grisly &dot; as wolues as hit weore; wenden in heore wyse &dot; wiþ sum kunnes ginne, wiþ a poynt of chekmat &dot; comen me wiþ-inne; and forsoþe ful neih &dot; hedde i foule fallen, bi-trapped in heore clokes &dot; and cau&yogh;t til heore preye.  And so dude I sikerly &dot; þorw my foule sunne, so fer þat I hedde &dot; be worþi to helle, ne hedde onliche i-ben &dot; þin vnymete Merci, þat euer is so redi &dot; and þi swete grace; þat after long abode &dot; whiles I lay in sunne, and wolde not arysen &dot; for non of þi callynges, ne for þi milde wouwynges &dot; þat þou þenne madest, al [min] vnþonkes &dot; derworþe lord, drouh me from myn enemy, so freoly & so frendly, þat I so wrecchedly &dot; folewode so faste.  ¶ Þat euer beo þou blessed &dot; in heuene and in eorþe, hei&yogh;ed and heried &dot; of al þat þou schope! for whon þe bale was most &dot; þen was þe bote next; þe grace of þe holigost &dot; hit taylede so.  For whonne þou se&yogh;e hit beo so &dot; þat I ne wolde arysen, ne my-self stonden &dot; a&yogh;eynes my foos, ne blenchen heore wyles, heore crokes and heore gyles, but slou&yogh; slugginde lyen &dot; slumbrinde in sunne:  ¶ Þenne come þou my leof &dot; my lemmon my deore, wiþ liht leytinde loue &dot; to seche me here.  ¶ Þou felle for me gostly &dot; from heuene to eorþe, and ruddest me raply &dot; of al þat þer was; &yogh;if I ly&yogh;e lodly &dot; þou reysedest me redily, and &yogh;if I fallynde was &dot; þou breyde me a&yogh;eyn.  ¶ At þe poynt of my fal &dot; whon I most dradde, þou kuddest þe quikly &dot; to make res-




cous.  And al fihte þou þus &dot; vche day neowe, to wite me and were me &dot; in gostliche weorre.  Þou vnderfonge bodiliche &dot; for me for to fihten, here in worldliche lyf &dot; a&yogh;eynes hem alle:  ¶ wiþ pouert and wiþ schome &dot; a&yogh;eyn þe saut of þe world; wiþ peyne & wiþ passion &dot; a&yogh;eyn þe flesches lustes; wiþ louhnesse and Mekenesse &dot; wiþ loue and studefastnesse, a&yogh;eyn þe þridde fo þe fend:  and al þou ouercome.  ¶ And tau&yogh;test me beo þi-self &dot; sendest me mi&yogh;te, forto weorre wiþ hem &dot; in þe selue wyse, þat I ne dredde meschef:  ne recchen of worldlich wo, of seknesse bodiliche &dot; or gostlich fondynge, wrong of luþer monnes werk &dot; or of wikked mouþes, of schome or of schendschupe &dot; wiþ-oute mi gult, but euer stonde wiþ þe &dot; in studefast herte, and þole þonkyndeliche &dot; al þat þou sendest.  For alle suche bales &dot; hose riht kennes, as witnesseþ holy writ &dot; beoþ toknes of blisse—¶ Iacobus: Omne gaudium existimate, fratres, cum in variis temptacionibus incideritis. Þer art þou redilich &dot; and stondest bi-sydes: wiþ alle þat beþ so biset &dot; and troubled in care / or in anguisse &dot; or wandreþ wawes Of þis worldly séé &dot; seilen and faren; / þi-self steerest þe schip &dot; & ledest to þe hauene Of euer-lastynde pes &dot; þer alle weoles aren, / and art in vch a such fiht &dot; in þe vanwarde, & makest scheld of þi-self &dot; þi lemmon to sparen. // Now mi dere lemmon &dot; whonne hit so fareþ / þat hose harde be stond &dot; haueþ þe to feere, / euer wolde I fihten &dot; and seilen in care / wiþ eni worldliche wo &dot; to haue þe so neere. / Euer-lastinde fiht &dot; leuer me ware, / to ben so sikerlich &dot; scheld at þi baneere, / þen after fikelynde weole &dot; for a gynge fare, / and leuen þe my lemmon &dot; my derlyng my dere.  ¶ A my deore lemmon &dot; whil I þe harde cluppe, wiþ loue-likynde þou&yogh;t &dot; lastinde in herte, / al siker am I schild &dot; a&yogh;eyn þat me werren, ne þar i dreden here res &dot; ne beo þei neuer so smerte. / Þer wol I resten &dot; and taken my truwe, þi-self stoppest my foos &dot; and makest hem to sturte, / and so me witerliche witest &dot; euer while i dwelle, of heore ferliche affrayes &dot; þat comen ouerþhwerte. // A mi swete lemmon &dot; my derlyng my deore, / hold euer my þou&yogh;t &dot; in siht of þi chere, / þat I ne flitte þe from &dot; in fiht þat is here, / but euer schild me wiþ þi-self &dot; to fiht in þi feere.  ¶ Mi swetyng mi derlyng, min hony-brid mi luffyng, swettest of alle þing:  &yogh;if me þat lastyng / of þi loue-likyng.  Do me for to serue þe, lere me forte loue þe &dot; louynde lord:  so þat onliche þi loue &dot; be al my likyng. A Ihesu my swete loue &dot; þat þou art wondur riche, as al-weldinde lord &dot; in heuene and in eorþe:  and pore þenne þou bi-come &dot; for me þat am so wrecched, whon þou in þi childhod &dot; weore leyd in þe cracche; schend þou weore and schomed &dot; of wikked mennes mouþes, fondet after wiþ þe fend &dot; on fele cunne wyse, and siþen atte laste &dot; schendfuliche & schomeliche, wiþ strong deþ & pyneful &dot; hongede on þe Roode.  ¶ Pore were þou furst boren &dot; of þi leue mooder, þat mayden is and moder &dot; of þe þat art hire fader.  For in þe borwh of Bethleem &dot; ne fonde þou no leuþe, wher in þi Bury-tyd &dot; þou mihtest þe resten, but in a wouhles hous &dot; a-midde þe strete, þat was a symple refuit &dot; in so cold a tyme.  Þer weore þou wounden &dot; and swaþeled in Ragges, and after coldliche i-leyd &dot; in a beestes Crubbe.  So woldest þou be conuersaunt &dot; and comuyn wiþ bestes, to maken vs caytyues &dot; þat beestlich liuen




heere, wiþ þi-self conuersaunt &dot; in heuene-riche blisse.  Þus poreliche bi-gunne þou &dot; Ihesu my swete lemmon, for to lede þi lyf &dot; in londe for me.  // But whon þou eldore weore &dot; þow wox more pore.  For furst in þi childhod &dot;  þou heddest to þi foode / þe Milk of þi mooder brest &dot; þe Maydenes pappe, and þi Moder redi &dot; euer whon þou woldest, & whon þou sore weptest &dot; to stille þe þerwiþ: ¶ But whon þou eldore was:  þou þat alle feddest, boþe foules in þe flyht &dot; & fissches in þe flod, men & alle beestes &dot; þat heere lyf leden, þoledest for defaute of mete &dot; mony hote honger, in bote of vre sunne &dot; as telleþ holy writ.  ¶ And þou þat þe heuene &dot; and al þis world wrou&yogh;test, ne heddest in al þis wyde world &dot; whon þou scholdest dyen, wher-on þou mi&yogh;test &dot; þin holy hed resten.  ¶ But euer bi-foren heddest þou &dot; in &yogh;ouþe and in elde, wher-wiþ þou mihtest &dot; hulen þin holy bones.  ¶ But atte laste of þi lyf &dot; in þi meste neode, whon þou for me so reuþly &dot; heng vppon þe Roode, þer ne heddest þou so muchel &dot; of al þis worldes wynne, wher-wiþ þin holy bodi &dot; þou mihtest inne folden.  ¶ Al þus my swete lemmon &dot; pore þou were þi-seluen, & to pouert of þis world &dot; sannest þow þe toke.  Pouert þow louedest &dot; and pouert þou tau&yogh;test, and treweli þou be-hi&yogh;test &dot; þin endeles blisse / to alle þat here for þi loue &dot; pouert and pyne, Mesey[s]e and Mischeef &dot; in pacience taken.  ¶ A swete lord &dot; hou scholde i ben riche / here vppon eorþe: & þou my leof so pore? . . . as þi-self weore pore &dot; for þe loue of me, for to beo riche wiþ þe &dot; in þin oune blisse; ffor wiþ pouert & wiþ wo &dot; schal me wele buggen. But pouert wiþ menske &dot; is eth forte þolen.  (B)ut þou lord for my loue &dot; wiþ al þat ilke pouert, þou weore schomeliche ischent &dot; reuyled and dispyset. For often men þe seiden &dot; schomeful wordes / & scornful hokeres:  longe weore al to tellen.  // But [more] schome þoldest þow &dot; þat neuer sunne wrouhtest; weore I-taken as a þeof &dot; & brou&yogh;t bifore luþer men, heþene houndes &dot; fforte be demed of hem, þat art þi-self demere &dot; and Iuge of alle worldes.  ¶ And þou lord þat art lyf &dot; of al monkuynde, weore dempned to þe deþ &dot; & þat to schomeliche deþ, and þe mon-quellere &dot; was to lyf i-saued; ffor alle þei cri&yogh;ede on þe &dot; so grisliche and loude: «honge Ihesu on Roode &dot; & leese out Barraban», and was þat Baraban a þef &dot; worþi forte dyen, þat wiþ tresun in þe Borwh &dot; hedde a mon quelled!  // But more schome þow þoledest &dot; my sunne for to beeten, whon sunfol men so viliche &dot; in þi face spitten.  A mi swete lemmon &dot; my derlyng my deore, ho mihte more schome þolen &dot; cristen or heþen, þen þat men so lodlich &dot; in his face spitten?  and þou in þi louesum leor &dot; þat angeles to biholden:  nare neuer folle, such schome þoledest!  & al þe þhou&yogh;te menske &dot; for þe loue of me, so þat þou mi&yogh;test wiþ þat foule spittyng &dot; wassche my soule, & maken hit louelich &dot; & schene in þi sihte.  For-þi þou biddest me &dot; euer þenke þer-vppon, and seist on þis wyse: Scito quoniam propter te mortificamur tota die; [propter te sustinui] obprobrium, operuit confusio faciem meam, «Vnderstonde, þou seist, and þenk &dot; þat I for þe loue of þe &dot; suffre schome & bismare: schendful spittyng &dot; of vnworþi men, heþene houndes &dot; amidde my face.  And þerfore ne dred þe nou&yogh;t &dot; ffor þe loue of me, to þole worldes schome &dot; despyt and wikked wordes Of wikked mennes mouþes &dot; wiþ-outen þi gult».  ¶ And schome




of alle schome &dot; soffredest þou lord, whon þou weore honged &dot; al mooder-naked: wiþ-oute cloþ or clout &dot; be-twene two þeues.  Also þei seiden &dot; þe envyous Iewes:  «He is worse þen a þef &dot; & more schome worþi, and þerfore hong him hei&yogh;e &dot; bi-twene hem boþe, as he þat is heore mayster &dot; & worse þen þei».  ¶ A Ihesu my lyues loue &dot; my derworþe lemmon, herte may to-bersten &dot; þat þeron þenkeþ, folliche as hit was &dot; in þi deolful deþ!  ¶ Þou þat art worschupet &dot; of al Monkuynde, of alle bales bote &dot; and angeles blisse:  mon for to worschupen & sauen from pyne, woldest of wikked men &dot; þole so muche schome.  ¶ Men speken mony tyme &dot; of wondres þat fallen, of selcouþ þinges, þat in þis world misliche &dot; ofte be-tyden:  ¶ But þis was þe moste wonder &dot; þat euer bifel in eorþe, wonder ouer wondres &dot; seþþe þis world bigon: þat onlepi kuynde kyng &dot; coround in heuene, þat schop alle schaftes &dot; and weldeþ alle þing, to worschupen his enemys &dot; wolde so mekelich, he þat is so louelich &dot; honge so schomelich, bi-twene two þeues &dot; as he were a þef.  ¶ A swete Ihesu swete leof, tech me forte loue þe &dot; so deore as þou louedest me &dot; my deore lemmon; so þat onlich þi loue &dot; beo euer al my likyng, my mourning my longyng, wiþ-outen eny endyng, amen. But my swete lemmon &dot; Inouh were þi pouert &dot; [&] þi muchele schome &dot; wiþ-outen oþer peynes.  But þe ne þhou&yogh;te neuer Inou&yogh; &dot; for to buggen folliche &dot; my loue al enterliche &dot; whil þi lyf laste.  // A swete Ihesu Merci: what pris settest on me?  Ne was neuere vnworþi þing &dot; half so deore abou&yogh;t!  For al þi lyf in eorþe &dot; euer was in muche swynk &dot; for me vnworþi wrecche, and euer þe lengor þe more; þat bifore þin endyng &dot; so harde þou swonk, & trauayledest so sore:  þat red blod þou swatest — Factus est sudor eius sicut gutte sanguinis decurren[tis] in terram; ffor as seynt Luc seiþ &dot; in his holy gospel: þou weore in so strong swynk &dot; þat þi swot as blod-dropes, ron from þin holy bodi &dot; doun vppon þe ground.  ¶ But what tonge may tellen &dot; what herte may þenken &dot; for serwe or for rouþe, of þat harde boffetyng, þat horlyng and defoulyng, þat þou þoledest schomelich: at þi furste takyng; whon þat Iudas Scariot &dot; brou&yogh;te helle-houndes, wiþ treson þe to taken &dot; & bringe til heore princes.  And hou heo þe bounden &dot; so egerlych & so faste, þat þe blod sprong out &dot; at þe fynger nayles:  as holy halwen hit siggen &dot; & writen is in boke.  And bounden þe so harde &dot; & ladde þe forþ ruydlich, betynde reuþlich, on Bac & on scholdres: and on vch a syde.  And bi-foren þe princes, buffeteden [þe] & scornden &dot; & blyndfellede þyn e&yogh;en, pleieden a-Bobbeþ &dot; & maden þe heor fool, & spitten in þi face &dot; mony tyme & ofte, and maden hit so wlatsum &dot; so bleyk & so blo: wiþ betyng & bustyng &dot; and spittyng & spoutyng; wiþouten eny merci: þei dihte þe so.  Þei grenneden vppon þe &dot; and waggeden heor heuedes &dot; and blatten out heore tonges &dot; and bonteden on þe schomeliche &dot; and maden þe þe mouwe. Siþen by-fore Pylate &dot; hou þow weore naked &dot; bounden til a pyler &dot; and scourget so sore; so þat þow ne mi&yogh;test &dot; none weys wrenchen: ne heore smarte lassches &dot; bi none gate blenchen.  ¶ Þer weore þou for my loue &dot; wiþ harde knotti scourges, swongen and beten &dot; so smart and so sore: so þat þi louely leor, þat was so briht and so cleer, was al to-fouled and I-schent, þi skin to-riuen




and to-rent; þer stremed on vche syde a flood, of water and of red blod: þow lord wiþ so meke mood &dot; þoledest al heore wille.  Siþen on þin hed was set &dot; a Coroune of scharpe þornes:  so þat after vche a þorn &dot; þe rede blod gon folwen.  ¶ Siþen &yogh;it þei beoten doun &dot; þe coroune vppon þin hed; and dresseden hit and þraste, and duden hit sitte faste, so þat þe scharpe þornes &dot; wente in to þe brayn.  ¶ Setten a reod in þin hond &dot; in stude of kynges septre, in scorn & in heþing, and maden to þe heor knelyng, and seiden «heil be þou kyng»: and spatten in þi teeþ.  And aftur al þat vileny, ne wolde þei not be þerbi, but luþurli & falsly &dot; dempned þe to þe deþ. A derworþe lord &dot; what schal I nou don?  Nou mai I liue no more, for serwe and for sore: now my dere lemmon &dot; schal vnderfonge deþ.  Nou mai I Murne strongly, nou mai I wepe bitterli; nou may I syke sore &dot; & serwen euer-more.  // A, now me leden him forþ &dot; to mount of Caluarie, to þe qualmstouwe &dot; to don him þere o dawe.  A, my deore lemmon &dot; he bereþ þe Roodetre: on his bare scholdre &dot; for þe loue of me; his bodi is so tendre &dot; his bones longe and lene: al stoupynde he goþ &dot; þat del hit is to seone.  ¶ A, mi swete lemmon, þe duntes þat þei smyte þe, þe serwe þat þei don þe!  on vche a syde þei þreste þe &dot; forþward vnwrestly, cri&yogh;inde hidously, to þi deþ hastily; & al þou þoledest louely: for me wrecche vnworþi.  Lord þat art almihti, &yogh;if me for þi merci &dot; muynde of þat vileny, and felyng at myn herte: þi peynes hou þei smerte.  // A swete Ihesu leoue lyf, hou mony men nou folewe þe &dot; for to wondren on þe; þy frendes ben sori &dot; and serwhfol in herte; þi foos folwen hokerly, and lyken in heore maystri, and horlen þe lodly &dot; in al þis worldes sihte. // Allas: nou þei han I-brou&yogh;t him &dot; þider þer þey wolen him slen. Now þei casten him doun &dot; and leien him on þe cros.  Now þei streynen out his lymes &dot; his senwes al to-bersten; his liþes breken out of Ioynt: þat non of hem may lasten.  ¶ Allas my deore lemmon &dot; hou may men for reuþe, a&yogh;eyn so muchel fordede &dot; do þe al þat wo?  To þe þat art so loueli, so feir and so freoly, and þoledest so mekeli &dot; al þat þei wolde do!  ¶ A Ihesu now þe driuen &dot; þe blunte vnruide nayles: þorw þi feire hondes &dot; and þi frely feet. Nou bersteþ þi skin &dot; þi senwes and þi bones; min herte cleueþ in my brest: for reuþe of þi mones.  ¶ A Ihesu swetyng, wher is eny wepyng, wher is welle of teres, to lauen on my leores, þat I neuere bi day &dot; stunte nor be nihte, nou I seo þi feire lymes &dot; so reuþli I-dihte.  Þe blood of þi woundes &dot; springes so breme, and stremeþ on þi white skin &dot; so reuþe to sene; þy Moder lokeþ þeron &dot; þat virgyne clene: hir serwe sit þe sarre &dot; þen þin as ich wene.  ¶ A: now þei setten vp þe cros &dot; & setten vp þe Roode-treo, & þi bodi al be-bled &dot; hongeþ þer-onne. ¶ A: Ihesu now þei setten þe cros &dot; in to þe morteis:  þi Ioyntes sturten out of liþ &dot; þi bones al to-scateren, þi woundes ritten a-brod &dot; for-goled so wyde: lord þat þe was wo bigon &dot; in þat ilke tyde!  ¶ A, my deore lemmon &dot; whon þou heddest al bled, þou wox al druye &dot; and gonne þhirste sore; þei boden þe to drinken &dot; Eysel and Galle, but whon þou tastedest þerof &dot; þow woldest no more.  // A: my swete lemmon &dot; teken al þyn oþer wo, þei bonteden vppon þe &dot; whon þou heng on roode, so mylde and so meke &dot; as hit weore




a lomb; lou&yogh;when þe to bisemare &dot; grennynde foule, wiþ schome schakinde here hed &dot; in hoker & in scorn, ¶ seiden in vbbreid &dot; «lo wher he hongeþ, þat couþe saue oþer men: and saueþ nou&yogh;t him-seluen».  ¶ Weo: lord: vre loue is luitel worþ &dot; þat costen þe so deore, and &yogh;it vnne we hit nou&yogh;t &dot; þat þou hit haue here, but folwen vr lustes &dot; in þe deueles fere, as þau&yogh; he be beter þen þou: and more worþ were.  ¶ Allas allas for reuþe &dot; þat I schal þe my lemmon, so foule seo demeynet: and myn is al þe gult; ¶ al for-drawen and for-rent, bi-spit & schomeliche schent, to sauen vs þer we weore: for þat was al þi cause.  ¶ A Ihesu swete lemmon: hou mai I nou libben: Nou I seo þe leoue lyf &dot; þe loue of myn herte, mi derlyng my longyng, mi blesset lord my swetyng, wiþ armes white and louely &dot; streyned so streytly &dot; wiþ-outen eny merci &dot; naked on þe Rode: so þat men may tellen &dot; al þin holy bones.  ¶ Þer þow hongedest reuþly, so cold and so blodi; al rau and wori: is þi swete bodi.  ¶ A swete Ihesu &dot; deore lemmon, nou þou di&yogh;est for me, hongynge on Rode-tre, & letest þin hed falle doun &dot; þat del hit is to se.  þe white of þin e&yogh;en &dot; is tornd upward.  ¶ A Ihesu &dot; nou deskeþ þe sonne.  Nou þe eorþe trembleþ: and þe stones bersten. Nou þe temple cleoueþ &dot; for serwe of my lemmon.  Nou rysen vp þe dede, in witnesse of þi godhede: & walken in Ierusalem &dot; as writen was biforen.  ¶ Allas noþing ne serwes &dot; ne noþing ne rewes: for my deore lemmon &dot; þat pineful deþ and schendful, wiþ-oute sake of sunne &dot; soffred on þe cros.  ¶ A mi deore lemmon, mi serwe mi blisse &dot; myn only lyues loue, þat di&yogh;edest so strong deþ: for al þis worldes lyf; þe pynfolest & reuþfolest &dot; þat euer þolede eni bodi, or mihte dyen onne: for þe loue of me:  ¶ A swete Ihesu þin ore &dot; Let me nou dyen &dot; in þi blisful armes, from al þe loue of þis world &dot; in to þe loue of þe; so þat only þi loue &dot; beo euer al my lykyng. But &yogh;it my derworþe leof &dot; whon þei hedden þe slayn &dot; al at heor wille, ne þ&yogh;ou&yogh;te hem not þat Inou&yogh;, þat þei se&yogh;e þi dede bodi &dot; so reuþli honge on Roode; ne wolde þei not spare þe &dot; de[d] ne o-lyue, but brouhte forþ Longius &dot; þat was a blynd kniht, and token him a scharp sphere &dot; to stinge þorw þin herte, so þat hit clef a-two &dot; and of þat ilke welle of lyf, þorw þat grisly wounde: runne two floodes: ¶ þi Riche precious blod &dot; þat al þe world bou&yogh;te, and þat deore holy water &dot; þat al þis world wosch Of sake and of synne, þat þei were fallen Inne: what þorw heore oune gult &dot; & Adames sunne.  ¶ A Ihesu swete lemmon &dot; hou kuyndeliche openest þou me: þi derworþe herte &dot; lyues and deþes, / fforte knowen witerli &dot; al þi loue þer-inne, and writen hit dernely &dot; in myn herte trewely, wiþ trewe loue-lettres: of þin herte-blood.  ¶ Wiþ wronge þenne schulde I þe &dot; al myn herte wernen:  seþþe þou hit bou&yogh;test &dot; so harde & so dere:  myn herte wiþ þin herte &dot; mi loue wiþ þi loue, mi soule wiþ al þi blisful bodi: & þin holy soule!  ¶ A, swete Ihesu gode leof &dot; let me be þi seruaunt, & do me forte loue þe &dot; louynde lord; set as depe þi loue &dot; to brennen in myn herte: as þou wiþ þe speres ord &dot; was stongen for me; so þat onliche þi loue &dot; be euer al my lykyng, mi &yogh;erning mi longyng, swete Ihesu heuene kyng, in þou&yogh;t and al my worching, wiþ-outen eny makyng &dot; of eny oþur mong. LAdi seinte Marie &dot; Moder & Mayden, muche was þe serwe &dot; set at þin herte, whon þou at þi sones deþ &dot; stoode him so neih!  Þou sei&yogh; al his serwes &dot; þat




was so harde bi-lad: ¶ I-streyned on þe Roode &dot; his bodi al on bloode, þe kene coroune vppon his hed: þat loueliche foode; ¶ His syde wiþ þe speres ord &dot; opened so wyde; bi feet and bi hondes &dot; to-reiht on vch a syde, þe stremes of his deore blood &dot; þat gunne doun glyde: Ladi wo was þe bi-gon: in þat ilke tyde.  ¶ Þou lokedest on his swete leor &dot; þi derlyng þi deore, houngynge reuþliche &dot; on Roode in þeues feere; þe peyne of his passion &dot; þe chaungyng of his cheere, þin herte stongen þorw-out &dot; þi deþ als hit weore — animam tuam pertransyuit gladius. ¶ Þou fel swonynde doun &dot; ofte als I wene, and sikedest & sobbedest &dot; ful sore bitwene; þi rode wox al won &dot; þin heu&yogh; al grene, þat was biforehond so briht &dot; so feir & so clene.  ¶ Ladi þe teres &dot; þat þou þere leete, þi breste & þi chekes &dot; maden al weete; þou lokedest vpward &dot; to him þat was so swete, & euer at þe ende &dot; ful sore þou dudest wepe.  ¶ Whon þou bi-heolde his woundes &dot; so grisly and grete, and þat þou scholdest him for-gon &dot; & bodiliche leete: þen wox in þi breste &dot; my ladi so swete, monyfold serwe &dot; and muchel vnymete.  ¶ Ladi for þat serwe &dot; þat sat þe so sore, þat þou heddest for him &dot; and he for þe &yogh;ore, to slaken out of serwe &dot; al þat þer-Inne wore: led hem to þi blisse &dot; al þat he þolede fore. LAdi Milde Marie &dot; Mooder of Merci, help of alle helplese &dot; and sunful of hele, socour of alle serwe &dot; & boote of alle bale, to alle þat trusten in þe &dot; and sechen þin helpe: ¶ help me Marie &dot; milde queene, ladi of heuene ... Emperisse and Mayden &dot; & Godus deore Mooder.  Derworþe ladi &dot; for to saue synful: Ihesu Crist bicom þi sone &dot; and dude þe þat menske; ffor vre sake weore þou maad &dot; Maiden Godes Mooder.  Neore þow nou&yogh;t as þou art &dot; hi&yogh;ed ouer alle, qween of alle blisse: &yogh;if synful ne weore.  For-þi ou&yogh;ten sunful &dot; calle to þe sikerly, for whom þou hast þin hey&yogh;nesse &dot; and þi muchele grace.  ¶ Maiden and Moder þou art: and his Mooder þou art, his hondewerk þou art &dot; his spouse and his dou&yogh;ter: his þat welde and wrou&yogh;te &dot; alle maner schaftes, þat regneþ ay in blisse &dot; wiþ-outen eny ende. ¶ A swete ladi Marie &dot; muchel is þat menske: euer to ben in blisse &dot; such a sones Mooder, wiþ al hol Maydenhod &dot; and Maydenes menske; and hast him so in baundoun &dot; and al at þi wille: þat he wole al þat þou wolt &dot; ouer-al be forþed.  And forte schewen vs þis &dot; he streihte þe his Riht arm &dot; as he heng on Roode &dot; and bouwede touward þe &dot; his derworþe hed &dot; as &yogh;if he seide to þe: «Moder al þat þou wolt &dot; schal ben at þi wille».  ¶ A swete ladi &dot; whi ne haue I euere &dot; by-fore myn herte ei&yogh;en &dot; &yogh;oure þreo serwes: þi sone i-streyht on Roode &dot; þorw-driuen feet and hondes &dot; wiþ Irene nayles, blodi his syde; and þou stode him bi &dot; and seynt Ion þe Ewangelist, weopynde on eiþer half &dot; wiþ serewhful sykes.  ¶ Whi ne bi-holde I euere &dot; þis in myn herte, and þenke þat hit was for me &dot; and for oþur sunfol, þat he rudde out of helle &dot; and &yogh;af vs heuene-blisse?  ¶ Þis þou&yogh;t wolde sikerliche &dot; cundle a brennynde loue; þat weore þe herte neuer so cold &dot; ne schulde neuer sunne &dot; ben folfuld in dede &dot; þer [þat] þou&yogh;t ware. A Ladi þi Ioye &dot; þou heddest of his vprist, after al þi serwe &dot; þe þridde day of his deþ; whon þou wiþ þin ei&yogh;en &dot; se&yogh;e him o-lyue, in vndedliche lyf &dot; to liuen wiþ-outen ende!  Þer com þe cumfort &dot; and Ioye after care: whon þou




se&yogh;e him glorifyet &dot; boþe god and mon, his bodi þat was seuenfold &dot; bri&yogh;tor þen þe sonne; blisful was þe swete siht &dot; þe to loken onne! // Ladi for þat blisse &dot; þat þou heddest þenne, bring me to þat blisse &dot; þat þou wonest Inne.  And parte wiþ me of þi deol &dot; in herte for to felen &dot; sum of his serwe &dot; þat þou for him heddest.  And help me þat I here mote dyen &dot; in oure boþes loue: and rysen at domes-day &dot; in oure boþes blisse; Þat I may þer felen &dot; þe fruit of bugginge: and &yogh;e brouken of me &dot; þat was so dere bou&yogh;t. A swete Ihesu sweete leof &dot; my lemmon my deore lord, swettest of alle þing &dot; my leue lyf my lyues loue: // þou me hast defendet &dot; a&yogh;eyn myn enemys þreo, wiþ al þi lyf &dot; wiþ þi deþ, and madest of me vnworþi: þi lemmon and þi spous, // and brou&yogh;test me so seliliche &dot; out of þe false word, as þin owne derling &dot; to þin owne boure, ¶ and as I weore þin owne brid &dot; here in to þi cage, to wone wiþ þi-self &dot; in þis holy place, þat no mon of al þis word &dot; ne þar me wiþ delen: but þi-self al one &dot; ¶ Ihesu my deore lemmon; where þat I may þe sen &dot; In muynde so priuely &dot; and wouwe þe so louely &dot; and cluppe þe swetely &dot; and clepe þe so redili, and as I were þi druri &dot; ay dwelle þe bi; ¶ wiþ a loue longyng &dot; and a stille mournyng, þat me ne schal beo lykyng &dot; in þou&yogh;t of worldliche þing, but in Ihesu heuene kyng, mi leue lyf mi derlyng, þat haþ me loueliche lad &dot; in to þis seli wonyng. ¶ A lord blessed mote þou be &dot; þat hast ordeynt for me &dot; boþe mete and drinke: cloþing and oþer þing &dot; & me ne þar not swynke, but only tende to þe: Ihesu blessed mote þou be.  ¶ A swete Ihesu swete leof &dot; my lyues loue my swetyng, þou hast maad me of nouht, fro þe deþ þou hast me bou&yogh;t, ffrom þe world in to þi chaumbre: leue lord þou hast me brou&yogh;t, and more blisse þou hast me hi&yogh;t: þen wiþ herte may be þou&yogh;t.  ¶ A, swete Ihesu my deore lemmon &dot; þat þus muchel hast don for me: what may I þenke &dot; what may I speke &dot; what may I worþly don: for þe loue of þe?  what may I &yogh;elde þe &dot; what may I þole for þe &dot; a&yogh;eyn þat þou hast þoled for me?  ¶ A, mi swete spouse &dot; mi deore loue: me be-houeþ þat þou beo &dot; eeþ for to paye, as I wot wel þat þou art; for a wrecche bodi and a weyk &dot; I haue heer on eorþe, þat I hedde of þi &yogh;ifte &dot; ful feir & ful clene, but I haue muchel enpeyred hit &dot; and lodliche I-fuiled.  ¶ But &yogh;it such as hit is, I &yogh;iue hit þe enterlyche &dot; to þi seruise: nayled and sprad faste in my roode &dot; in þis holy ordre, as þou weore nayled for me &dot; in þin harde roode.  ¶ And here wol I dwellen &dot; wiþ þe my swete lemmon: and neuer-more wol I &dot; of my Roode comen, neuer whil þat I lyue: for þe loue of þe;  þen wol I beo grauen &dot; heer vnder þe eorþe &dot; as þou weore grauen for me: and on domes-day wol I rysen a&yogh;eynes þe, and wenden þenne al hom wiþ þe: and wonen in þi blisse &dot; þat þou greiþest nou &dot; vche day to me.  ¶ A swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; so murie and so swete hit is &dot; forte dwellen heere, on Rode as þi fere, to þole pyne for þi loue &dot; þat bou&yogh;test me so dere. FOr whon I in my soule &dot; wiþ al hol muynde &dot; seo þe so reuþly &dot; hongen on Rode &dot; þi body al on blode, þi limes al to-rey&yogh;te &dot; þi Ioyntes al to-pli&yogh;te, þi woundes and þi leoue leor &dot; þat was so briht and so cleer, ben now mad so grisli &dot; and þow lord so mekely &dot; tok hit al so louely &dot; for me þat was þin enemy: þenne fele I redili &dot; a tast wonder ferli &dot; of þi derworþe loue &dot; þat




precious druri, þat fulleþ myn herte so &dot; þat al worldliche wo: hit makeþ me þinken hony-swet &dot; whoderward so euer i go.  ¶ Swete lord þin ore &dot; where is eny blisse &dot; a&yogh;eyn þe tast of þi loue &dot; at þin owne come: Whon þyn oune Moder &dot; so louely of chere, þyn owne bodi on þe cros &dot; derworþe deore, in þe selue liknesse &dot; þat þou þenne were, beodeþ me to cluppen &dot; as myn owne fere. ¶ Þenne ginneþ þe loue &dot; to springen at myn herte, and glouweþ vp in my brest &dot; wonderliche hote: þe loue-teres of myn neb &dot; rennen ful smerte, my song is likynge of loue &dot; al wiþ-oute note.  I lepe on him raply &dot; as grehound on herte, al out of my-self &dot; wiþ loueliche leete: and cluppe in myn armes &dot; þe cros bi þe sterte, þe blood I souke of his feet &dot; þat sok is ful swete.  ¶ I cusse and I cluppe &dot; and stunte oþerwhile, as mon þat is loue-mad &dot; and seek of loue-sore: i loke on hire þat him bringeþ &dot; and heo biginneþ to smyle, as þau&yogh; hire likede wel &dot; and wolde i dude more.  I lepe eft þer i was &dot; and auntre me þore, i cluppe and I cusse &dot; as I wood wore: I walewe and i souke &dot; i not whuche while, and whon I haue al don &dot; &yogh;it me luste more.  ¶ Þenne fele I þat blood &dot; in þou&yogh;t of my Mynde, as hit weore bodilich &dot; warm on my lippe: and þe flesch on his feet &dot; bifore and beohynde, so softe and so swete &dot; to cusse and to cluppe.  Heo openeþ hire Mantel &dot; þat ladi so kuynde and happeþ vs þer-vnder &dot; in þat muri fitte; &yogh;if eni mon vs askeþ &dot; þeer men may vs fynde, as hem þat lykeþ þer þei ben &dot; & loþ is for to flitte.  ¶ Swete lemmon leoue lyf / mony wo haue þei &dot; þat are not holliche wiþ þe: in þin holi cluppyng.  But wel is me þat I may, euermore niht and day, al þis world forsaken &dot; and beo wiþ þe al one.  ¶ Also my swete Ihesu &dot; my deore lyues loue, as þou on þe roode &dot; sperred wiþ þe nayles &dot; &yogh;eue þi soule out of þi bodi &dot; for þe loue of me: ¶ also my swete lemmon &dot; I as on my Rode &dot; sperred in myn ordre &dot; from worldliche murþes &dot; and fleschliche lustes &dot; in peyne wiþ þe, &yogh;eue my soule &dot; and my bodi &dot; and al myn herte blisse: wiþ al þe lust of my lyf &dot; to þe loue of þe.  And I preye þe derworþe lord &dot; for þyn holy nome: þat þou receyue loueli &dot; of me wrecche vnworþi &dot; þat &yogh;ifte so freoly &dot; al in to þi merci, þat I neuer loue oþur þing &dot; but al one þe.  ¶ For I ne may nou&yogh;wher my loue &dot; my bodi ne my soule: bi-setten better elles-where &dot; þen on þe al one, so louelich lord as þou art &dot; so worþiful and so precious, in bodi & in soule: and eke in deite, þat hast only in þi-self &dot; alle maner þinge: wherfore eny þing &dot; mai be loue-worþi.  ¶ For &yogh;if I my wrecche loue &dot; beode for to sullen, and sette þeron as hei&yogh; pris &dot; as herte may beo-þenken: &yogh;ut weore al þat for nou&yogh;t &dot; þat þou ne most hit hauen.  For sikerliche my swete lemmon &dot; þou hast don more þerfore: and &yogh;it woltou more don &dot; þen I my-self con þenken: And þerfore I coude not &dot; ymagen so hei&yogh; pris, þat þou nast don heer-tofore &dot; moni-fold more.  For lord whon þat I nas nou&yogh;t &dot; þenne þou me maadest: and þat lyk þi-seluen; and for þou madest me lord &dot; al þat I am: I am al þat I am &dot; holden to þe one.  For in þat ilke makyng: þou madest me so clanly &dot; so feir and enterly, wiþ-outen lac of eny lyme: lyk þi-self al-one, wiþ al my fyue wittes &dot; resonable as angel, and þin holy angel &dot; a-signet my seruaunt, and nou&yogh;t onliche he: but also þi-seluen; and don me muchel more, &yogh;iue me wiþ my cristendam &dot; al hol þi-seluen, and muchel more þen I con &dot; my-self vnderstonden.  ¶ But &yogh;it þow [þat]




madest me &dot; þou art so noble in þi-self &dot; an hondred þousend fold &dot; and vnymete more: þen al þis world may þenken.  And also muchel as þou art worth &dot; am I holden to þe, þat al þi-self hast &yogh;iuen to me: and madest me of nou&yogh;t. // Wherfore in þat wit &dot; þat þou lord hast &yogh;iuen to me, wot I wel forsoþe and seo &dot; þat I am holden &dot; fully to loue þe for me, and þat þou hast me don &dot; muchel more monyfold &dot; þen I con seon or knowen; and &yogh;it a þousend-fold &dot; and vnimete more &dot; am I holden for þat þou art &dot; more þen for my-seluen. But swete Ihesu my lyues loue &dot; nou&yogh;t onliche madest þou me of nou&yogh;t: But þerto, whon I was loren þorw myn oune defaute, þou founde me and bou&yogh;test me &dot; a&yogh;eyn wiþ þi blod.  But what &yogh;eue þou for me &dot; to bugge me to blisse?  forsoþe lord a deore prys: þi-self to þe deþ.  ¶ But swete lemmon leoue lyf &dot; of my furste makyng: am I holden to þe &dot; muchel more þen I am &dot; & more þen I con þenken; and siþen of my fyndyng &dot; & of my deore buggyng, þat þou me bou&yogh;test wiþ þi deþ &dot; am I nou double holden.  But so muchel monyfold &dot; and vnimete more: is in þat deore buggyng &dot; þi derworþe loue i-kud &dot; þen was in þat makyng, þat I ne wot what I may siggen &dot; ne rikene þeronne.  ¶ But ouer in(!) al þis worldes wit &dot; may nempnen or þenken &dot; am I holden so fer &dot; and so muchel more: þat al þat euer may beo þou&yogh;t &dot; al nis as riht nou&yogh;t &dot; a&yogh;eyn þat I am holden.  ¶ But &yogh;it my swete derlyng &dot; my lyues loue my swetyng, not onliche madest þou me of nou&yogh;t &dot; and after whon þat I was loren &dot; a&yogh;eyn þou bou&yogh;test me wiþ þi deþ &dot; so deore vppon þe Roode: But &yogh;it ouer al þis &dot; þou hast me trewely be-het &dot; al þi-self in blisse; þou þat me madest so &dot; and me so deore bou&yogh;test, woldest wedde me to þe &dot; & &yogh;iuen euermore þi-self &dot; al hol to be myn owne. A swete Ihesu my leoue lyf &dot; my lemmon my gode lord, mi swetyng my derlyng &dot; swettest ouer alle þing: ¶ what schal I nou siggen?  ffor nou am I þrefold holden for to louen þe &dot; // In as muchel as I am &dot; // and þrefold more þen I con &dot; // and þrefold wiþ-outen meþ more þen in al þis world: wiþ herte may beo þou&yogh;t.  ¶ On is for my makyng &dot; ¶ anoþer for my buggyng, þe þridde is for my weddyng: to þe myn owne spouse.  ¶ A Mi swete lemmon: what schal I nou don: þat I nam but o-fold &dot; and I-holden to þe &dot; al my-self þrefold, muche more vche fold: þen herte may þenken?  ¶ Nou swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; my derworþe lemmon: al þe þou&yogh;t þat i con &dot; onliche hit is for þe, where þat I may fynde loue: Inou&yogh; for to &yogh;eue þe. // And þau&yogh; I wuste where &dot; so muche loue to fynden: ne haue I wher to leggen hit &dot; ne wher-in to don hit.  ¶ For wel I wot þe soþe &dot; þat þau&yogh; my sely herte &dot; weore widdore and largore &dot; þen is al þis wyde world: &yogh;it weore hit not suffisant &dot; half þat loue to holden, ne þe þousend part &dot; þerof to biclosen; ffor wel I wot sikerly &dot; þat neede hit moste bersten: wiþ strengþe of loue-longyng &dot; to þe my leoue lord.  ¶  Swete Ihesu my leoue lyf &dot; my lemmon so deore, ffeir swetely and freo &dot; and louely of chere, let me beo þi seruaunt &dot; and serue þe here: þat I may in þi blisse &dot; sitte þe neere.  ¶ Swete Ihesu my lyues loue, þat sittest so hei&yogh;e in heuene aboue, ¶ what schal I don &dot; ¶ what schal I seyen &dot; ¶ what schal I þenken in þi loue?  For hit is so wonder muchel &dot; wiþ-outen eny bigynnynge, þat þou me formedest




furst &dot; and madest lyk þiself of nou&yogh;t; ¶ and eft &yogh;it hit is so muchel in þe middel worchyng: þat wiþ þi bodiliche lyf &dot; þou hast me siþen longe I-sou&yogh;t, and wiþ þi deþ þat was so hard &dot; vppon þe Roode so deore bou&yogh;t; and hei&yogh;test me more monyfold: þen wiþ herte may be [þ]ou&yogh;t.  For al þi-self al one &dot; alweldinde lord, verrey god and soþfast mon &dot; in bodi and in soule, þou hast me hi&yogh;t trewely &dot; forte ben myn oune, in more blisse endeles &dot; þen herte may þenken.  And tokne special &dot; bifore mony oþure, þow takest me of þi cortesy &dot; as þin owne druri: Drawen out of þis false world: my trichour and myn enemy, and put me her priueli &dot; to lere me louely &dot; ffor to singgen swetely &dot; in þin oune cage: so þat þou beo al my song &dot; wiþ loue-teres euer among, þat i do neuer þat wrong &dot; to maken eni oþur mong &dot; of no worldliche þrong &dot; til tyme of myn heþen-&yogh;ong, þat I heþene to þi-self: make my passage. But swete Ihesu leue lyf &dot; my lyues loue mi lemmon, loue þe wol I as I con &dot; and leten for no mon.  For nou wot I what I wol don.  Siþen þat þe loue of þe &dot; is so vnymete muchel ¶ þat I ne con not þenken þerof no bigynnyng &dot; for my furste makyng; ¶ ne I ne con seo þerof &dot; mesure in þe middel &dot; for my middel buggyng &dot; wiþ þi deore di&yogh;ing; ne I ne con þer-onne &dot; þenke non endyng &dot; for my trouþe pli&yogh;tyng &dot; þat I made at chirche-dore: whon I was a child &yogh;yng &dot; to þyn owne weddyng: ¶ Swete Ihesu swete leof &dot; siþen I ne con of þi loue &dot; be-gynnyng ne endyng, forsoþe swete lemmon &dot; swettest of alle þing, a-midde þi loue I wol me don &dot; bitwene to þin armes; ¶ and þere wo I lslepen and waken, and þere my preyers maken, murþes in mournyng &dot; þer wol I taken, and al þis worldes lykyng &dot; for þi loue forsaken.  ¶ Þer wol I cluppen & cussen, and swete loue-sawes ine wissen, and in a lykynde baþ &dot; baþen of blisse, þer flowe teres of loue &dot; wiþ-outen eny lisse.  ¶ Þer wol I souken of þi syde, þat openeþ a&yogh;eyn me so wyde, wiþ-outen eny fluttiyng &dot; þer wol I a-bide, as hit was opened for me &dot; so blessed be þat tyde.  ¶ Þer wol I lyuen and d[e]ye, bi-loken in þyn armes twey&yogh;e, and þe my lef loueliche preye, þat þou me so wiþ þi loue t[e]y&yogh;e, þat I may of þi merci wiþ þi-self stei&yogh;e, to loue þi fader in siht of his ey&yogh;e.  ¶ A swete Ihesu swete lef &dot; my deore herte my lyues loue, mi lyf &dot; mi deþ &dot; mi blisse: ffor þou ordeyndest me &dot; to þi deore lemmon, Bi-twene þin armes ley I me, bi-twene myn armes cluppe I þe; nou &yogh;if me felyng &dot; in þe wiþouten ending, and hold me in þi kepyng, swete Ihesu heuene kyng.  Amen.
